{"questionId":"19305","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>In a class of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn></math> students, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>19</mn></math> play tennis, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> play both tennis and volleyball, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> do not play&nbsp;either sport.</p>\n<p>The following Venn diagram shows the events “plays tennis” and “plays volleyball”.&nbsp;The values <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math> represent numbers of students.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/365586a2f181cba9bc60d4531c87c2665ed8901d.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the probability that a randomly selected student from the class plays tennis or&nbsp;volleyball, but not both.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>valid approach&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em>eg&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>21</mn></math>&nbsp;students,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><mn>30</mn></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;<img src=\"__IMG__/a2c40839b1ee50b1c92da30c562961213b46689e.png\"></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>21</mn><mn>30</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1 N2</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19305","referenceCode":"20N.1.SL.TZ0.S_1b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the probability